snippet.textDisplay:
I'm gonna put this out here now: I'm not a fan of Deep Fusion. Too many of the photos (I'd guess around 25 percent of them in this video) look artificially synthesized to the point where they feel more like CGI than actual photo graphs. I understand the desire to capture more detail, but the overall effect on the contrast, lighting and sometimes even the color palette just didn't look natural. I'd prefer a decently detailed photo that looks natural, over an artificially enhanced photo.


Of course, the iPhone photos may look better when they aren't being presented in a video that's been run through YouTube's notoriously crappy video transcoding.

snippet.textDisplay:
In pretty much every photo, I was heavily changing my opinion on which looked good between all four. I would pause before Linus said anything too, to not skew my opinion. More than half the time the photos that I thought looked awful, Linus was saying we're the "superior photos".

Overall, I preferred the Pixel 4, then Note 10, then iPhone. This is weird because I'm really not a fan of Google at all, or their phone lineup.

I also really just didn't like how much detail iPhone removed from people's faces. Photo editing software exists for a reason. Capture a person as they are, truly as they are, then edit it after if you feel the need to present them differently. I want the default option to capture the "real" person, without any smoothing effect.
